The former class comprised all who had the ius imaginum, i. e. all (whether patricians or plebeians) whose fathers or ancestors had held curule office in the State. (V. Glossary, nobilitas, and n. on § 11, 1. 3,§ 72, l. 1.) This new aristocracy of titled families was for a long time as exclusive and as close as the old patrician aristocracy 3 its claim was less constitutional and its methods more unscrupulous. Known in politics as the party of the optimates, it received its first blow from the Gracchi, and from that time its serried phalanx was not unfrequently broken by some intruding novus homo such as Marius and Cicero.
